2":"1350–1402","1352–1386":"1352–1386","1352–1436":"1352–1436","1302–1353":"1302–1353","1307–1367":"1307–1367","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1436":"1436","1402":"1402","1302":"1302","1367":"1367","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1386":"1386","1320":"1320","about 1352":"about 1352","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","Orrell Hall, Wigan, England":"Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Wigan, , Lancashire, England":"Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Ince-in-Makerfield, Lancashire, England":"Ince-in-Makerfield, Lancashire, England","Turton, Lancashire, England":"Turton, Lancashire, England","Orrell, Lancashire, England":"Orrell, Lancashire, England","Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ince","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational name from Ince in Makerfield (Lancashire), Ince (Cheshire), or Ince Blundell (Lancashire). The placenames derive from Proto-Welsh <i>ïnïs</i> ‘island’.","possibly a post-medieval West Midlands variant of <b>Hints</b>, a habitational name from either of two places called Hints (Staffordshire, Shropshire). The placenames probably derive from Proto-Welsh <i>hïnt</i> ‘way, path’ + Middle English plural <i>-es</i>.","possibly a variant with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i> of <i>Inn</i>, from residence at an <i>inn</i> or <i>inns</i>, from Middle English <i>in</i> (singular) or <i>innes</i> (plural) ‘tavern, lodging(s), tenement(s)’. There seems also to have been some confusion with Scottish   Innes  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hince","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Michel.","English: variant of   Ince  .","Altered form of English   Hains  ."]},{"name":"Ence","meanings":["English: variant of   Ince  .","Americanized form of South German   Enz  , a short form of   Anselm  .","History: Two brothers, Johannes and Gottlieb Enz, immigrated from northern Switzerland to southern Utah around 1860. Their descendants bear the surname <i>Ence</i>."]},{"name":"Innes","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   McInnis  , from Gaelic <b>Mag Aonghuis</b> ‘son of Aonghus’.","Scottish: habitational name from the barony of Innes in Urquhart (Morayshire), named from Gaelic <i>inis</i> ‘island’.","English: variant of   Ince  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":0,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":9,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":54,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Ince was born in 1328, in Ince-in-Makerfield, Lancashire, England, her father, Richard Ince, was 26 and her mother, Helen Ince, was 21. She had at least 3 sons with Adam De Orrell II. She died in Orrell, Lancashire, England."},"et":{"1328–":"1328–Surnud","1328–Female":"1328–Surnud","1320–1372":"1320–1372","1350–1402":"1350–1402","1352–1386":"1352–1386","1352–1436":"1352–1436","1302–1353":"1302–1353","1307–1367":"1307–1367","1352":"1352","1350":"1350","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1436":"1436","1402":"1402","1302":"1302","1367":"1367","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1386":"1386","1320":"1320","about 1352":"umbes 1352","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","Orrell Hall, Wigan, England":"Wigan, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wigan, , Lancashire, England":"Wigan, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ince-in-Makerfield